<h2><span style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">What</span></h2>
<div style="text-align: justify;"><span
 style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">T</span><span
 style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">he goal of group
readings is the </span><span
 style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">collective study
of topics of importance in some "hot" areas of computer science, at the
moment especially pertaining social networks and related topics. Group
readings are an attempt to share the burden of studying the paramount of
literature in these fields, so as to ease widespread of theirknowledge
within our groups. </span><br
 style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">
<span style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">These
readings may be particularly useful to PhD students of Computer
Engineering and Computer Science groups.</span><br
 style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">
<span style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">Some topics
covered by next readings will be: </span><br
 style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">
<br style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">
<span style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">- Modelling
of social networks </span><br
 style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">
<span style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">- Algorithms
for information retrieval in social networks, especially the Web </span><br
 style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">
<span style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">- Stability
of algorithms for social networks </span><br
 style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">
<span style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;">- Related
aspects of clustering and data mining<br>
<span style="font-family: courier new,courier,monospace;"><br>
